RE|REG|A1080816|1272579|2671926|FCC|06/15/2010|0|SPECIAL CONDITIONS:  1. The FWS and the FCC will be notified by telephone within 24 hours by Verizon Wireless upon the discovery of injured and/or dead wildlife.  Verizon Wireless will provide the FWS a written notification, summarizing the event, within
RE|REG|A1080816|1272579|2671926|FCC|06/15/2010|1|30 days.  2.  Upon notification of take by Verizon Wireless, the FCC will contact the Service within 24 hours upon the take of nine Newell’s shearwaters or upon the take of nine Hawaiian petrels during the life of the tower so that the FWS may reevaluate
RE|REG|A1080816|1272579|2671926|FCC|06/15/2010|2|project impacts prior to reaching the authorized take limit.  3.  Access to the tower site will be provided by Verizon Wireless to the FWS and Hawaii Division of Forestry and Wildlife personnel with same-day notification so that they may independently
RE|REG|A1080816|1272579|2671926|FCC|06/15/2010|3|monitor for downed seabirds.  4. Should take of either species occur, the depository designated to receive specimens of any Newell’s shearwaters or Hawaiian petrels that are found near the tower is the B.P. Bishop Museum, 1525 Bernice Street, Honolulu,
RE|REG|A1080816|1272579|2671926|FCC|06/15/2010|4|Hawaii, 96817 (telephone: (808) 847-3511).  If the B.P. Bishop Museum does not wish to accession the specimens, contact the Service’s Office of Law Enforcement in Honolulu, Hawaii (telephone (808) 861-8525: fax (808) 861-8515) for instructions on
RE|REG|A1080816|1272579|2671926|FCC|06/15/2010|5|deposition.
