RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|0|Background
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|1|On August 18, 2017, Apex Towers, LLC (Applicant) filed Antenna Structure Registration (ASR) Application No. A1087113 for a 93-meter (305-foot) tall lattice tower in Copper Hill, Virginia.  National notice was published via the Commission’s
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|2|ASR system on August 28, 2017.  Leanne D. Carico (Requester) filed a timely Request for Further Environmental Review (Request) alleging that the proposed tower may pose a risk of contamination to “a central source of fresh water” to Requester’s farm and
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|3|livestock via chemicals leaching from the tower and associated equipment, a health risk to people at a nearby elementary school, and a risk to aviation safety.  Requester further alleges that the proposed tower site is accessible only via a single,
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|4|one-lane road with low weight bridges that goes through flood zones, which may cause traffic problems, and that there was previously a dispute regarding the proposed site’s property lines.
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|5|On November 20, 2017, the Wireless Telecommunications Bureau (Bureau) directed Applicant to provide additional information regarding (a) flood zones, tree removal, and erosion control measures the Applicant plans to take, and (b) all correspondence with
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|6|the U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service (USFWS) documenting informal consultation regarding the northern long-eared bat (Myotis septentrionalis) and the Indiana bat (Myotis sodalis).  Regarding only the northern long-eared bat, the Bureau allowed the applicant
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|7|to provide copies of documentation that it completed the U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service’s northern long-eared bat 4(d) rule streamlined consultation process in lieu of copies of documentation of informal consultation.
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|8|Applicant responded on November 30, 2017 via a letter with attached documentation from its consultant, Environmental Corporation of America (ECA) (see Letter from Ben Salter, Principal Scientist, ECA to Jennifer Flynn, Attorney Advisor, FCC/WTB/CIPD, Nov.
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|9|29, 2017 (Response Letter)).  In that letter, ECA asserts that the proposed project area is not in a flood zone and in support provides a copy of FEMA Flood Insurance Rate Map No. 51063C0095C, Panel 95 of 400.  ECA also states that it has an erosion and
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|10|sediment control plan and provides in attachments its detailed plans to be implemented before, during, and after construction (see Response Letter and Erosion & Sediment Control Plan (ES-1), Notes (ES-2), Details (ES-3), and Compound Grading Profile
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|11|(ES-4)).
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|12|By letter dated September 6, 2017, attached to Response Letter, USFWS provided ECA with a list of threatened and endangered species that may occur in the project area and/or be affected by the proposed project, which included the threatened northern
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|13|long-eared bat (Myotis septentrionalis), the endangered Indiana bat (Myotis sodalis), and the endangered Mitchell’s satyr butterfly (Neonympha mitchellii mitchellii); no critical habitats are found within the project area (see Letter from USFWS, Virginia
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|14|Ecological Services Field Office, to Whom It May Concern, RE: Project Name T2557 – Copper Hill, Sept. 6, 2017).  In its Response Letter, ECA states that it finds that the proposed project will “not affect any federally listed species identified by USFWS
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|15|as potentially occurring within the project area with the exception of the federally endangered Indiana bat and the federally threatened northern long-eared bat.”  Further, ECA asserts that if tree clearing is limited to less than one acre and occurs
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|16|between September 15 and April 15, then the proposed project is “not likely to adversely affect the Indiana bat and the northern long-eared bat,” and if Applicant wants to conduct tree clearing outside of this period, it must first consult further with
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|17|USFWS.  These conditions are reflected in the USFWS Self-Certification Letter with attached Species Conclusions Table, as is ECA’s finding that the Mitchell’s satyr butterfly is not found in the project area (see Self-Certification Letter and attached
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|18|Species Conclusions Table from Cindy Shultz, Field Supervisor, Virginia Ecological Services, USFWS Virginia Field Office to Applicant, RE: Apex Towers – VAFYCH01 (Copper Hill), November 16, 2017 (Self-Certification Letter)).
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|19|Decision
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|20|Requester has provided no basis for her allegation that the proposed tower project poses a risk of chemicals leaching into fresh water sources, and we do not know of any reason why it would. The FCC’s radiofrequency exposure guidelines are
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|21|designed to ensure human safety (see https://www.fcc.gov/general/radio-frequency-safety-0 for further information).  Given that there are no antennae currently at the site, it is premature to assert that radio frequency emission levels at the site will
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|22|exceed the applicable permissible exposure (MPE) limits set forth in the Commission's rules.  Regarding the alleged risk to aviation safety, we note that the Commission generally defers to the FAA on matters that concern air navigation safety.  See, e.g.,
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|23|47 C.F.R. §§ 17.7, 17.23.  We agree with Applicant’s determination that the proposed project area, including the access road, is not in a flood zone.  To the extent any traffic problems will occur as the result of tower, we have no reason to believe that
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|24|they would be exist beyond the several days it would take to install the tower, and thus conclude that they would not constitute a significant effect on the human environment.  We further find that an alleged past dispute over property ownership at or
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|25|near the proposed project site is not a potential environmental effect.  Therefore, we deny the Request.
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|26|Nevertheless, construction of the proposed tower project will require significant tree removal on a steep ridgetop, and we are therefore concerned about the potential for erosion and sediment run-off into local water sources.  The Virginia Department of
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|27|Conservation and Recreation (VADCR) recommends that Applicant should “implement[] and strict[ly] adhere[] to applicable state and local erosion and sediment control/storm water management laws and practices” in order “[t]o minimize adverse impacts to the
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|28|aquatic ecosystem as a result of the proposed” tower project (see Letter from S. Rene Hypes, Project Review Coordinator, Commonwealth of Virginia, Department of Conservation and Recreation, to Brandon Smith, ECA, Oct. 10, 2017).  In ECA’s email to the
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|29|Virginia Department of Game and Inland Fisheries (VADGIF), Applicant committed to follow “[s]tate Erosion and Sediment Control Guidelines…, thus minimizing potential for indirect effects to sediment runoff into surface waters” (see Email from Brandon
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|30|Smith, ECA, to Amy Ewing, VADGIF, Sept. 11, 2017).  We find that the erosion and sediment control plans submitted by ECA are sufficient to minimize the potential for erosion and sediment run-off to occur, and we therefore condition the grant of ASR
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|31|Application No. A1087113 on Applicant’s implementing and adhering to them.
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|32|Also, because ECA’s finding that the proposed tower project is not likely to adversely affect the northern long-eared bat (Myotis septentrionalis) and the Indiana bat (Myotis sodalis) hinges on Applicant’s commitment to clear less than one acre of trees
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|33|and to perform all tree clearing activities outside of roosting season, i.e., between September 15 and April 15, we further condition the grant of ASR Application No. A1087113 with these same limitations of area and time period, as well as require that
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|34|Applicant must first consult further with USFWS in the event it wishes to clear trees from more than one acre or perform any tree clearing activities between April 16 and September 14.
RE|REG|A1105075|1304438|2704134|FCC|12/08/2017|35|In sum, we deny the Request, but condition the grant of ASR Application A1087113 as described above regarding erosion and sediment control, and tree clearing.
RE|REG|A1152355|1304512|2704208|FCC|12/14/2017|0|NEPA resolved per FONSI letter dated 12/13/2017, file number A1090820.
RE|REG|A1343778|1304513|2704209|FCC|12/14/2017|0|NEPA resolved per FONSI letter dated 12/13/2017, file number A1085821.
RE|REG|A1304235|1304524|2704220|FCC|12/14/2017|0|NEPA resolved based on FONSI letter dated 12/6/2017.
RE|REG|A1136295|1304628|2704324|FCC|12/21/2017|0|NEPA resolved per FONSI letter dated 12/20/2017, file number A1087020.
