RE|REG|A1379792|1304885|2704581|FCC|01/12/2018|1|CONDITION:  A1089007 with the following conditions (from pages 6-8 in EA):
RE|REG|A1379792|1304885|2704581|FCC|01/12/2018|2|“The Service does recommend the use of BMP's [Best Management Practices] to reduce sedimentation and erosion and the preservation of as much existing vegetation adjacent to the stream as possible. All disturbed areas should be mulched and revegetated with
RE|REG|A1379792|1304885|2704581|FCC|01/12/2018|3|native woody and herbaceous species. Due to the proximity of the project site to a known hibernaculum the Service recommends that if any trees cannot be avoided, they should only be cut between all unavoidable tree clearing occur between November 15 and
RE|REG|A1379792|1304885|2704581|FCC|01/12/2018|4|March 15 to avoid impacts during fall swarming and spring staging. Therefore, we recommend that the habitat and surrounding trees be saved wherever possible. If trees cannot be avoided, any unavoidable tree removal should only occur between November 15
RE|REG|A1379792|1304885|2704581|FCC|01/12/2018|5|and March 15 to avoid impacts to northern long-eared bats as they have been documented hibernating in the area. In areas where timber rattlesnakes or their dens are known or likely to exist, clearing, construction, and maintenance activities (mowing,
RE|REG|A1379792|1304885|2704581|FCC|01/12/2018|6|cutting, burning, etc.) should be avoided at least 100 feet from ridges and areas of exposed rock and should be conducted from November 1 to March 1, when timber rattlesnakes are hibernating. You have indicated that an Army Corps of Engineers permit may
RE|REG|A1379792|1304885|2704581|FCC|01/12/2018|7|be required for the stream crossing. If you intend to clear trees prior to issuance of a 404 and/or 401 permit the following two conditions must be adhered to: 1) Section 7 consultation for the Indiana bat between the Service and the Corps of Engineers
RE|REG|A1379792|1304885|2704581|FCC|01/12/2018|8|must be completed; and 2) No tree clearing on any portion of the parcel should occur until both the Corps and Ohio EPA anticipate the issuance of both a 404 and a 401permit authorizing the project as a whole is imminent. This will ensure that clearing
RE|REG|A1379792|1304885|2704581|FCC|01/12/2018|9|will be limited to the footprint of the project as it is ultimately permitted, and no unnecessary clearing will occur. No tree clearing should occur until these two conditions have been satisfied.”
