RE|REG|A1121481|1310274|2709971|FCC|05/06/2019|0|NEPA resolved per FONSI letter granted May 1, 2019, file number A1121481.
RE|REG|A1121481|1310274|2709971|FCC|05/06/2019|1|Conditioned on the USACE wetland impact permit dated November 16, 2018. Compliance with the USFWS’s “Standard Protection Measures for the Eastern Indigo Snake” dated August 12, 2013 is a requirement for the project area. The USACE also stipulated that
RE|REG|A1121481|1310274|2709971|FCC|05/06/2019|2|all gopher tortoise burrows, active or inactive, shall be excavated prior to site manipulation in the vicinity of the burrow. The USACE further required that should excavation of any potentially occupied burrows, active or inactive, individuals are
RE|REG|A1121481|1310274|2709971|FCC|05/06/2019|3|required to first obtain state authorization via Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) Authorized Gopher Tortoise Agent permit. The USACE required that the excavation method selected shall minimize the potential for injury
RE|REG|A1121481|1310274|2709971|FCC|05/06/2019|4|of an indigo snake. It is our understanding that should this be required, the applicant shall follow the excavation guidance provided in the most current FWC Gopher Tortoise Permitting Guidelines found at http://myfwc.com/gophertortoise. The
RE|REG|A1121481|1310274|2709971|FCC|05/06/2019|5|USACE requested that if an indigo snake is encountered, that the snake must be allowed to vacate the area prior to additional site manipulation in the vicinity. Holes, cavities, and snake refugia other than gopher tortoise burrows shall be
RE|REG|A1121481|1310274|2709971|FCC|05/06/2019|6|inspected each morning before planned site manipulation of a particular area, and if occupied by an indigo snake, no work shall commence until the snake has vacated the vicinity."
